The build system isn't directly runnable from this directory layout, but the C is straightforward and correct. Let me verify the key properties by inspection:

- `gen_put_len`: `len` → `buf[0] = len ^ ~erase_value` (1 byte) or `buf[0] = (len|0x80) ^ ~ev`, `buf[1] = (len>>7) ^ ~ev` (2 bytes)
- `fcb_get_len`: XOR back with `~ev`, check bit 7 → decoded is 1 or 2 bytes, validate ≤ `FCB_MAX_LEN`

Edge cases verified:
| Input | erase_val | buf | decoded | result |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| len=5 | 0xff | [0x05] | 5 | return 1 |
| len=200 | 0xff | [0xC8, 0x01] | 200 | return 2 |
| len=16383 | 0xff | [0xFF, 0x7F] | 16383 | return 2 |
| erased | 0xff | [0xFF, 0xFF] | 32767 (>FCB_MAX_LEN) | return -ENOMSG |
| len=5 | 0x00 | [0xFA] | 5 | return 1 |
| len=200 | 0x00 | [0x37, 0xFE] | 200 | return 2 |
| erased | 0x00 | [0x00, 0x00] | 32767 (>FCB_MAX_LEN) | return -ENOMSG |

The implementation is complete. The function appears at `subsys/fs/fcb/fcb.c:230` and is the inverse of `fcb_put_len` — it reverses the XOR-with-`~erase_value` encoding, detects 1 vs 2 byte length encoding via the high bit, validates the decoded length against `FCB_MAX_LEN` (which also catches erased/uninitialized flash), and returns the number of bytes consumed (1 or 2) as the callers in `fcb_elem_info.c` expect.


